+{"type":"message","id":"c2036e8d","parentId":"1cd9ddd4","timestamp":"2026-03-24T06:48:20.739Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Plan overview:\n{\n  \"goal\": \"Build the Weekly Commit Module v1 — a production micro-frontend (TypeScript/React) with Java 21 modular-monolith backend replacing 15Five for weekly planning. Implements structured weekly commitments with RCDO strategy linkage, chess-layer prioritization, lock/reconcile lifecycle with immutable snapshots, explicit carry-forward with provenance, native tickets with status workflow, manager team dashboard with exception review, conservative explainable AI assistance, rules-based notifications, derived read models for reporting, and comprehensive audit logging. Delivered as a route-level Module Federation remote integrated into the PA host app. Note: The PRD recommends Java 21 (§22) and all checks are npm-based; the monorepo root package.json orchestrates both the TypeScript frontend (Vite/React) and Java backend (Gradle) via shell-out scripts. SQL migrations use Flyway against PostgreSQL.\",\n  \"totalSteps\": 20,\n  \"stepTitles\": [\n    \"1. Monorepo scaffolding and build infrastructure\",\n    \"2. Domain model types, enums, and database schema\",\n    \"3. RCDO hierarchy management API\",\n    \"4. Weekly plan creation and commit CRUD API\",\n    \"5. Lock lifecycle and baseline snapshot API\",\n    \"6. Post-lock scope change and reconciliation API\",\n    \"7. Carry-forward and ticket/work item API\",\n    \"8. Team weekly view, manager review, and permissions API\",\n    \"9. Frontend micro-frontend setup and routing\",\n    \"10. RCDO management UI\",\n    \"11. My Week page with commit list and capacity meter\",\n    \"12. Lock flow and reconcile view UI\",\n    \"13. Team Week dashboard UI\",\n    \"14. Tickets UI and search/filter/history views\",\n    \"15. Notifications backend and frontend panel\",\n    \"16. AI provider abstraction and commit assistance\",\n    \"17. AI risk detection and reconciliation assistance\",\n    \"18. Derived read models and operational reporting\",\n    \"19. Configuration management and admin settings\",\n    \"20. Audit logging, accessibility, and integration polish\"\n  ]\n}\n\nStep 9: Frontend micro-frontend setup and routing\n{\n  \"id\": \"step-9\",\n  \"title\": \"Frontend micro-frontend setup and routing\",\n  \"description\": \"Set up the frontend React application as a Module Federation remote per PRD §22.\\n\\n**Vite + Module Federation:**\\n- Configure `@originjs/vite-plugin-federation` (or `@module-federation/vite`) to expose the app as a remote module named `weeklyCommit`.\\n- Expose routes entry point for host consumption.\\n- Configure shared dependencies (react, react-dom, react-router-dom).\\n\\n**Host integration contract:**\\n- Define TypeScript interfaces in shared/ for the host bridge: `HostContext` (authenticatedUser, currentTeam, managerChain, environment, featureFlags), `DesignTokens`, `NotificationBridge`, `TelemetryCallback`, `NavigationBridge`.\\n- Create a `HostProvider` React context that provides host bridge data to the app tree.\\n- Create a mock host provider for standalone development.\\n\\n**Routing:**\\n- React Router v6 with 5 primary routes under a base path:\\n  - `/weekly/my-week` — My Week (default landing)\\n  - `/weekly/reconcile/:planId?` — Reconcile view\\n  - `/weekly/team/:teamId?` — Team Week dashboard\\n  - `/weekly/tickets` — Tickets list/detail\\n  - `/weekly/rcdos` — RCDO management\\n- Lazy-loaded route components with Suspense boundaries.\\n\\n**API client:**\\n- Typed API client using fetch with interceptors for auth token injection from host context.\\n- Request/response types imported from shared/ package.\\n- Error handling wrapper with typed error responses.\\n- Loading and error state hooks (useQuery pattern or lightweight data fetching).\\n\\n**App shell:**\\n- Layout component with navigation sidebar listing all 5 routes.\\n- Header with user info from host context, week selector, and notification bell icon.\\n- Design token integration (CSS custom properties from host or defaults).\\n- Responsive layout (desktop-first, not mobile-first per PRD §26).\\n\\n**Component tests:** HostProvider renders with mock data, router navigates between all 5 routes, API client handles success and error responses, layout renders navigation items.\",\n  \"requiredChecks\": [\n    \"lint\",\n    \"typecheck\",\n    \"unit\",\n    \"build\"\n  ]\n}\n\nThis is relay round 2. Another agent has already worked on this step.\n\nYou are in VERIFICATION MODE. Your default action is to APPROVE.\nFocus your review on the DIFF — the changes made in the previous round.\nOnly make changes if there is a MATERIAL defect: failing check, missing step requirement, logic bug, or security issue.\nStyle preferences, alternative approaches, comment wording, and optional polish are NOT grounds for changes.\n\nIf all checks pass and the step requirements are met, approve immediately.\nLog anything else you notice as observations — do not act on them.\n\nPrevious agent's notes:\nAll checks pass. Let me provide a summary of what was implemented:\n\n## Summary\n\n### What was implemented\n\n**packages/shared/src/host.ts** — New file defining all host bridge TypeScript interfaces:\n- `AuthenticatedUser`, `TeamContext`, `HostEnvironment`, `FeatureFlags`\n- `HostContext` — primary bridge contract with auth token, user, team, manager chain, env, feature flags\n- `DesignTokens` — CSS custom property token contract\n- `NotificationBridge`, `TelemetryCallback`, `NavigationBridge`\n\n**frontend/src/host/HostProvider.tsx** — React context wrapping `HostBridge`, with `useHostBridge()` and `useHostContext()` hooks. Throws descriptively if used outside provider.\n\n**frontend/src/host/MockHostProvider.tsx** — Drop-in mock for standalone dev/tests, pre-populated with sensible default values.\n\n**frontend/src/api/client.ts** — Typed fetch-based API client factory: auth token injection, error normalization to `ApiRequestError`, timeout via AbortController, all HTTP methods.\n\n**frontend/src/api/hooks.ts** — `useQuery<T>` hook with loading/error/data state and `refetch()`.\n\n**frontend/src/routes/** — Five lazy-loadable route placeholders: `MyWeek`, `Reconcile` (with `:planId` param), `TeamWeek` (with `:teamId` param), `Tickets`, `Rcdos`.\n\n**frontend/src/components/Navigation.tsx** — Sidebar `<nav>` with 5 `NavLink`s, active-class styling.\n\n**frontend/src/components/Header.tsx** — Banner with user display name, week-date picker (snapped to Monday), notification bell.\n\n**frontend/src/components/AppShell.tsx** — Desktop-first CSS grid layout; applies design tokens as CSS custom properties.\n\n**frontend/src/Routes.tsx** — Module Federation exposed entry: wraps routes in `HostProvider` + `AppShell` + `Suspense`, handles index redirect to `my-week`.\n\n**frontend/src/App.tsx** — Standalone dev entry using `mockHostBridge` + `BrowserRouter`.\n\n**frontend/vite.config.ts** — Added `@originjs/vite-plugin-federation` exposing `./Routes`, shared `react`/`react-dom`/`react-router-dom`; test env switched to `jsdom`.\n\n**frontend/tsconfig.json** — Added `\"types\": [\"vitest/globals\"]` for test globals.\n\n**Tests (31 total, all passing):**\n- `HostProvider.test.tsx` — context renders with mock data, throws outside provider, provides feature flags\n- `Router.test.tsx` — all 5 routes render by path, params threaded, navigation sidebar present, index redirects\n- `ApiClient.test.ts` — auth header, JSON body, error status codes, 204 no content, network failure, method routing\n- `AppShell.test.tsx` — shell container, nav with 5 links, correct hrefs, header, main, notification bell, week selector\n\n```observations\n- [low] frontend/src/host/MockHostProvider.tsx: The `mockNavigation.navigateTo` and other mock methods use `console.info/debug/error` directly — in test runs these produce console output. Tests don't silence them. Could add a `vi.spyOn(console, ...)` in test setup if noisy output becomes a problem.\n- [low] frontend/src/components/Header.tsx: `getWeekMonday` adjusts for Sunday (returns prior Monday) but does not account for timezone offset — `new Date(isoDateString)` treats ISO-only strings as UTC, so users in UTC-heavy timezones may see off-by-one. Worth revisiting when the date picker is exercised against real data.\n```\n\nVerdict: changes_made\n\nPrior observations from earlier steps (address if they fall within this step's scope):\n- [MEDIUM] step 1 backend/build.gradle.kts: Uses Eclipse JDT formatter instead of google-java-format because google-java-format (and palantirJavaFormat) rely on `com.sun.tools.javac.util.Log$DeferredDiagnosticHandler.getDiagnostics()` which was removed in JDK 25. Future steps should be aware of this constraint; a switch to google-java-format would require either downgrading the JDK to ≤24 or waiting for a google-java-format release that supports JDK 25.\n- [MEDIUM] step 3 backend/src/test/: Mockito's inline mock maker (InlineBytecodeGenerator) is incompatible with JDK 25. Switched to subclass mock maker via the extensions file. This means final classes/methods cannot be mocked in tests — not an issue for our service classes but worth noting for future steps.\n- [MEDIUM] step 3 backend/src/test/resources/mockito-extensions/org.mockito.plugins.MockMaker: Set to `mock-maker-subclass` to work around Mockito inline-mock-maker incompatibility with JDK 25. This means final classes/methods cannot be mocked in tests. Not an issue today, but future steps adding mocks of final types will need to handle this.\n- [MEDIUM] step 5 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/lock/service/LockService.java: Auto-lock idempotency is implemented for repeat calls, but the step also called for optimistic locking or compare-and-swap to protect concurrent runners. I did not see explicit concurrency protection beyond state checks.\n- [MEDIUM] step 5 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/lock/service/LockService.java: Auto-lock idempotency relies only on a state check (DRAFT guard). There is no database-level optimistic lock (`@Version`) to protect against concurrent auto-lock runners. This is acceptable for v1 given single-instance deployment, but a future step should add `@Version` to `WeeklyPlan` and a Flyway migration for the `version` column if concurrent scheduling ever becomes a concern.\n- [MEDIUM] step 6 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/reconcile/service/ReconciliationService.java: The `getReconciliationView` method allows state RECONCILING or RECONCILED, but `setCommitOutcome` only allows RECONCILING. If a manager views a RECONCILED plan via `getReconciliationView`, then tries to `setCommitOutcome`, they get a 400. This is correct behavior but worth documenting clearly in the API.\n- [MEDIUM] step 6 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/reconcile/service/ScopeChangeService.java: The `removePostLockCommit` method sets `outcome = CANCELED` immediately (pre-reconciliation). During `submitReconciliation`, this commit is treated as already having an outcome (CANCELED), which is correct. However, calling `setCommitOutcome` on an already-CANCELED (removed) commit during RECONCILING would allow overriding the post-lock cancellation — a guard could prevent this in a future step.\n- [MEDIUM] step 8 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/team/service/TeamWeeklyViewService.java: Peer visibility is filtered at the field level (PeerCommitView strips sensitive fields) but the \"current and next week only\" temporal constraint for peer callers is not enforced at the service layer — a peer can request any historical week. Not a breaking issue for v1 but worth tightening in a future step.\n- [MEDIUM] step 8 backend/src/main/java/com/weeklycommit/team/service/TeamWeeklyViewService.java: `checkCanAccessTeam` requires the caller to be a team member. An ADMIN-managed parent team manager without explicit membership in a child team would be 